03955nam a22006015i 9780300252897DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002528977 a10.12987/97803002528972doi  a(DE-B1597)555532  a(OCoLC)1153765371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aE169.1 7aPOL0310002bisacsh04a9732231 aSmith, Rogers M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThat Is Not Who We Are! :bPopulism and Peoplehood /cRogers M. Smith. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCastle Lecture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. A cacophony of stories -- t2. What makes a good story of Peoplehood? -- t3. Who are we Americans now? -- tAfterword. On doubts that may remain -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can liberals offer “stories of peoplehood” that can compete with illiberal populist and nationalist stories? Rogers Smith has long argued for the importance of “stories of peoplehood” in constituting political communities. By enabling a people to tell others and themselves who they are, such stories establish the people’s identity and values and guide its actions. They can promote national unity and unity of groups within and across nations. Smith argues that nationalist populists have done a better job than liberals in providing stories of peoplehood that advance their worldview: the nation as ethnically defined, threatened by enemies, and blameless for its troubles, which come from its victimization by malign elites and foreigners. Liberals need to offer their own stories expressing more inclusive values. Analyzing three liberal stories of peoplehood—those of John Dewey, Barack Obama, and Abraham Lincoln—Smith argues that all have value and all are needed, though he sees Lincoln’s, based on the Declaration of Independence, as the most promising.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aNational characteristics, American. 0aPopulism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069231040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300252897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300252897.jpg  a978-3-11-069231-0  YUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-PLWb2020